Marcuss descriptive statistics: how many meanings per language above chance?

A simple way to summarize this data is to check how many meanings are guessed above chance per language.

First, lets get a vector with the language names which well use for looping:

languages <- unique(field$Language)

# Check:

languages
## [1] "DE" "SR" "VA" "EN" "BR" "PA"

Put this into a tibble:

meanings_per_language <- tibble(Language = languages)
meanings_per_language$N_over_chance <- NA

# Check:

meanings_per_language
## # A tibble: 6 x 2
##   Language N_over_chance
##   <chr>    <lgl>        
## 1 DE       NA           
## 2 SR       NA           
## 3 VA       NA           
## 4 EN       NA           
## 5 BR       NA           
## 6 PA       NA

Loop through languages and get the N of items that have > 1/12 accuracy:

for (i in seq_along(languages)) {
  this_lang <- languages[i]
  these_avgs <- filter(field, Language == this_lang) %>%
    group_by(Meaning) %>% 
    summarize(ACC = mean(ACC))
  meanings_per_language[i, ]$N_over_chance <- sum(these_avgs$ACC > 1/12)
}

Check the results:

meanings_per_language

##   Language N_over_chance

## 3 VA                  12
## 4 EN                  12
## 5 BR                  12
## 6 PA                  10

Looks good. We want to do this for all of the six languages an then correlate these tables with the same tables from the other languages.

We can re-use the languages vector from above for this.

Create an empty 6 * 6 matrix (filled with NAs) to be filled with all the languages:

M <- rep(NA, length(languages) * length(languages))
M <- matrix(M, nrow = length(languages))

# Append row and column names:

rownames(M) <- languages
colnames(M) <- languages

# Check:

M
##    DE SR VA EN BR PA
## DE NA NA NA NA NA NA
## SR NA NA NA NA NA NA
## VA NA NA NA NA NA NA
## EN NA NA NA NA NA NA
## BR NA NA NA NA NA NA
## PA NA NA NA NA NA NA

Create two copies of this matrix, one for the correlation coefficients, another one for the p-values:

r_vals <- M
p_vals <- M

Loop through languages and create distance matrices:

for (i in seq_along(languages)) {
  # Cross-tabulation:
  
  this_tab <- with(filter(field, Language == languages[i]), table(Meaning, Choice))
  
  # Transform into distance matrix object (needed for Mantel test):
  
  this_tab <- as.dist(this_tab)
  
  # Save this in an object with the name pattern "EN_tab" etc.:
  
  assign(str_c(languages[i], '_tab'), this_tab)
}

Loop through languages and put this information into the corresponding matrices:

for (i in seq_along(languages)) {
  lang1 <- languages[i]
  for (j in seq_along(languages)) {
    lang2 <- languages[j]
    if (lang1 != lang2) {
      # Retrieve previously stored distance matrices:
      
      tab1 <- get(str_c(languages[i], '_tab'))
      tab2 <- get(str_c(languages[j], '_tab'))
      
      # Perform correlation:
      
      this_mantel <- mantel.rtest(tab1, tab2, nrepet = 999)
      
      # Store correlation value and p-value:
      
      r_vals[i, j] <- this_mantel$obs
      p_vals[i, j] <- this_mantel$pvalue
      
    }
  }
}

Check results:

## Correlation values:

round(r_vals, 2)

## DE   NA 0.67 0.55 0.79 0.52 0.40
## SR 0.67   NA 0.59 0.71 0.41 0.41
## VA 0.55 0.59   NA 0.63 0.54 0.66
## EN 0.79 0.71 0.63   NA 0.71 0.56
## BR 0.52 0.41 0.54 0.71   NA 0.49
## PA 0.40 0.41 0.66 0.56 0.49   NA

What are the p-values?:

p_vals
##       DE    SR    VA    EN    BR    PA
## DE    NA 0.001 0.001 0.001 0.001 0.003
## SR 0.001    NA 0.001 0.001 0.013 0.004
## VA 0.001 0.001    NA 0.001 0.001 0.001
## EN 0.001 0.001 0.001    NA 0.001 0.001
## BR 0.001 0.008 0.001 0.001    NA 0.001
## PA 0.003 0.004 0.001 0.001 0.001    NA

These need to be corrected for performing 15 correlations:

# Vector of adjusted p-values from upper triangle of the matrix:

adjusted_p <- p.adjust(p_vals[upper.tri(p_vals)], method = 'bonferroni', n = 15)

# Replace lower triangle with NAs to avoid confusion:

p_vals[lower.tri(p_vals)] <- NA

# Save adjusted p-values back into upper triangle:

p_vals[upper.tri(p_vals)] <- adjusted_p

# Check:

p_vals
##    DE    SR    VA    EN    BR    PA
## DE NA 0.015 0.015 0.015 0.015 0.045
## SR NA    NA 0.015 0.015 0.195 0.060
## VA NA    NA    NA 0.015 0.015 0.015
## EN NA    NA    NA    NA 0.015 0.015
## BR NA    NA    NA    NA    NA 0.015
## PA NA    NA    NA    NA    NA    NA

The only ones that dont significantly correlate with each other after correction are SR ~ BR and SR ~ PA. All others are correlated, even if correcting for 15 tests.

This completes this analysis.
